<span class=\"zDocsFeedbackButtonText\"> Feedback</span></span></div></div><div class=\"zDocsTopicActionsMobile\"><button aria-label=\"Show topic actions\" data-toggle=\"dropdown\" id=\"zDocsTopicActionsMobile\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"ico-ellipsis-h\"><use xlink:href=\"#ico-ellipsis-h\"></use></svg></button><div class=\"dropdown-menu zDocsDropdownMenu zDocsTopicActionsMobileDropdown dropdown-menu-right\"></div></div><div style=\"flex-basis: 100%; height: 0px;\"></div><ul class=\"zDocsTopicPageDetails\"><li class=\"zDocsTopicPageDate css-cinqea\">Last Updated<span class=\"css-cinqea\">Okt 18, 2024</span></li><li class=\"zDocsAiTopicSummaryDetailsItem\"><button class=\"zDocsAiTopicSummaryButton\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"ico-topic-summary\"><use xlink:href=\"#ico-topic-summary\"></use></svg>Summarize</button></li><li class=\"spacer\" role=\"presentation\"></li><div class=\"zDocsLabelWrapper\"><ul><li class=\"zDocsLabel\"><a aria-describedby=\"hyperLinkFacetsTooltip\" class=\"css-ettsdk\" data-tooltip-content=\"Search all site by tag: Uniface\" data-tooltip-id=\"hyperLinkFacetsTooltip\" href=\"/de-DE/search?labelkey=prod_uniface\" stylesprops=\"[object Object]\"><svg aria-label=\"Tag\" class=\"ico-tag\" role=\"img\"><use xlink:href=\"#ico-tag\"></use></svg>Uniface</a></li><li class=\"zDocsLabel\"><a aria-describedby=\"hyperLinkFacetsTooltip\" class=\"css-ettsdk\" data-tooltip-content=\"Search all site by tag: 10.4\" data-tooltip-id=\"hyperLinkFacetsTooltip\" href=\"/de-DE/search?labelkey=uniface_10.4\" stylesprops=\"[object Object]\"><svg aria-label=\"Tag\" class=\"ico-tag\" role=\"img\"><use xlink:href=\"#ico-tag\"></use></svg>10.4</a></li></ul></div></ul></header><div class=\"zDocsTopicPageBody\" data-prismjs-copy=\"Copy\" data-prismjs-copy-error=\"Copy failed! Use Ctrl + C instead.\" data-prismjs-copy-success=\"Copied!\"><div class=\"zDocsTopicPageBodyContent\" dir=\"ltr\"><div id=\"zDocsAiSummaryContaineruniface_104idu1665702544495.html\"></div><div><article class=\"hascomments\" data-page=\"bundle:uniface_104/enus/idu1665702544495.html\" id=\"bundle:uniface_104/enus/idu1665702544495.html\"><main role=\"main\"><article aria-labelledby=\"ariaid-title1\" class=\"dita\" id=\"idu1665702544495\" role=\"article\">\n<div class=\"body refbody\"><p class=\"shortdesc\">Direct the Uniface Router to start the Uniface Server in the environment of the user.\n </p>\n<section class=\"section\" id=\"idu1665702544495__section_w1949ab1b5b1_w1950ab1b5_w1951ab1\">\n<p class=\"p\" id=\"idu1665702544495__p_d138320e1_d138321e1_d138322e1\">\n<span class=\"keyword cmdname\">/su</span>\n</p>\n</section>\n<section class=\"section\" id=\"idu1665702544495__section_lcx_f2l_vvb\"><h2 class=\"title sectiontitle\" id=\"d517837e58\"> Description </h2>\n<p class=\"p\" id=\"idu1665702544495__p_d138326e1_d138327e1_d138328e1\">The <span class=\"keyword cmdname\">/su</span> switch directs the Uniface\n        Router to set the environment for the Uniface Server at start-up to that of the logon\n        user.</p>\n<p class=\"p\" id=\"idu1665702544495__p_d138329e1_d138330e1_d138331e1\">Use the <span class=\"keyword cmdname\">/su</span> switch in the following\n        places:</p>\n<ul class=\"ul\" id=\"idu1665702544495__ul_hnv_32l_vvb\">\n<li class=\"li\" id=\"idu1665702544495__li_d48761e1_d48762e1_d48763e1\">In the path declaration for a UST in the [SERVERS]\n          section of the Uniface Router's assignment file <span class=\"ph filepath\">urouter.asn</span>\n</li>\n<li class=\"li\" id=\"idu1665702544495__li_d48764e1_d48765e1_d48766e1\">In the path declaration of the client’s assignment\n          file </li>\n</ul>\n<div class=\"note note note_note\" id=\"idu1665702544495__note_jnv_32l_vvb\"><span class=\"note__title\">Note:</span> On Microsoft Windows, when you want to call out to\n        COM, SOAP, or web services from a Uniface Server, you should use the <span class=\"keyword cmdname\">/su</span>\n        switch for the Uniface Server's UST in the Uniface Router’s assignment file to prevent\n        problems with permissions.</div>\n<p class=\"p\" id=\"idu1665702544495__p_d138332e1_d138333e1_d138334e1\">The logon behavior is different on Windows, Unix and\n        Linux. <span class=\"ph\">\n<span class=\"keyword cmdname\">/su</span> is not supported in iSeries. </span></p>\n</section>\n<section class=\"section\" id=\"idu1665702544495__section_k21_gfl_vvb\"><h2 class=\"title sectiontitle\" id=\"d517837e103\"> Windows </h2>\n<p class=\"p\" id=\"idu1665702544495__p_d138338e1_d138339e1_d138340e1\">For Microsoft Windows platforms, the\n          <span class=\"keyword cmdname\">/su</span> switch causes the Uniface Server to start in the environment of the\n        user. If this environment is not present, Windows creates one before using it. Without the\n          <span class=\"keyword cmdname\">/su</span> switch, the Uniface Server uses the environment of the Uniface\n        Router.</p>\n</section>\n<section class=\"section\" id=\"idu1665702544495__section_irh_hfl_vvb\"><h2 class=\"title sectiontitle\" id=\"d517837e118\"> Unix </h2>\n<p class=\"p\" id=\"idu1665702544495__p_d138344e1_d138345e1_d138346e1\">For Unix, the Uniface Router starts the Uniface Server\n        using the <span class=\"keyword cmdname\">/bin/su</span> command, performing a full user logon using\n          <span class=\"ph filepath\">.profile</span>. Without the <span class=\"keyword cmdname\">/su</span> switch, the Uniface\n        Server gets the user and group IDs of the user, but the environment of the Uniface Router.\n        In those situations where the <span class=\"keyword cmdname\">/bin/su</span> command is not allowed (for\n        example, in security situations), use the <span class=\"keyword cmdname\">-nosu</span> command line switch.</p>\n</section>\n</div>\n</article></main></article>\n</div></div><div class=\"contentPlaceholder\" style=\"height: 500px;\"><div class=\"contentContainer zDocsSideBoxes\"><div><h5 aria-level=\"5\" class=\"css-g931ng\">Related Links</h5><ul><li><a class=\"css-ettsdk\" href=\"/de-DE/bundle/uniface_104/page/cza1665702544590.html\" stylesprops=\"[object Object]\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"ico-related-link\"><use xlink:href=\"#ico-related-link\"></use></svg>/nosu</a><p>Direct the Uniface Router to start the Uniface Server via the remote shell -rsh.</p></li><li><a class=\"css-ettsdk\" href=\"/de-DE/bundle/uniface_104/page/pjq1665702723793.html\" stylesprops=\"[object Object]\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"ico-related-link\"><use xlink:href=\"#ico-related-link\"></use></svg>Define Uniface Server Types (USTs)</a><p>Each UST identifies a specific Uniface Server configuration. It can be defined in the assignment file of the Uniface Router, or it can be provided to the Uniface Router by a Uniface Server that has been started manually.</p></li></ul></div></div></div></div><div class=\"bottomFeedback\"><div aria-labelledby=\"bottomFeedbackText\" class=\"bottomFeedbackContent\" role=\"group\"><span class=\"bottomFeedbackText\" id=\"bottomFeedbackText\">Was this topic helpful?</span><div class=\"bottomFeedbackButtonGroup\"><a data-backdrop=\"static\" data-target=\"#feedbackModal_bottom_2528501\" data-toggle=\"modal\" href=\"#\" role=\"button\" type=\"button\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"ico-thumbs-up\"><use xlink:href=\"#ico-thumbs-up\"></use></svg><span>Like</span></a><a data-backdrop=\"static\" data-target=\"#feedbackModal_bottom_2528501\" data-toggle=\"modal\" href=\"#\" role=\"button\" type=\"button\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"ico-thumbs-down\"><use xlink:href=\"#ico-thumbs-down\"></use></svg><span>Dislike</span></a></div></div></div><div style=\"position: fixed; bottom: 170px; right: 70px; cursor: pointer; transition-duration: 0.2s; transition-timing-function: linear; transition-delay: 0s; z-index: 3; opacity: 0; visibility: hidden; transition-property: opacity, visibility;\"><button aria-label=\"Scroll to top\" class=\"zDocsScrollTopBtn\" data-tooltip-content=\"Scroll to top\" data-tooltip-id=\"zDocsBackToTopToolTip\" id=\"zDocsScrollToTop\" type=\"button\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"ico-next\"><use xlink:href=\"#ico-next\"></use></svg></button></div></body></html>", "text": "/su Add to My Topics Add selected topic and subtopics Add Topic & Subtopics with topic head Add entire publication Watch Download PDF Save selected topic Save selected topic and subtopics Save entire publication Share Email Link Copy Link Feedback Last Updated Okt 18, 2024 Summarize Uniface 10.4 Direct the Uniface Router to start the Uniface Server in the environment of the user. /su Description The /su switch directs the Uniface Router to set the environment for the Uniface Server at start-up to that of the logon user. Use the /su switch in the following places: In the path declaration for a UST in the [SERVERS] section of the Uniface Router's assignment file urouter.asn In the path declaration of the client’s assignment file Note: On Microsoft Windows, when you want to call out to COM, SOAP, or web services from a Uniface Server, you should use the /su switch for the Uniface Server's UST in the Uniface Router’s assignment file to prevent problems with permissions. The logon behavior is different on Windows, Unix and Linux. /su is not supported in iSeries. Windows For Microsoft Windows platforms, the /su switch causes the Uniface Server to start in the environment of the user. If this environment is not present, Windows creates one before using it. Without the /su switch, the Uniface Server uses the environment of the Uniface Router. Unix For Unix, the Uniface Router starts the Uniface Server using the /bin/su command, performing a full user logon using .profile . Without the /su switch, the Uniface Server gets the user and group IDs of the user, but the environment of the Uniface Router. In those situations where the /bin/su command is not allowed (for example, in security situations), use the -nosu command line switch. Related Links /nosu Direct the Uniface Router to start the Uniface Server via the remote shell -rsh. Define Uniface Server Types (USTs) Each UST identifies a specific Uniface Server configuration. It can be defined in the assignment file of the Uniface Router, or it can be provided to the Uniface Router by a Uniface Server that has been started manually. Was this topic helpful? Like Dislike"}